Resources for Keyboard-Focused Development

Here are some useful resources that will help you test and implement keyboard-friendly web applications.

No Mouse Days

I created the tool “No Mouse Days” to be a little bit cheeky but to my surprise people actually used it.

The idea is to have a package you can install that turns off the mouse cursor in your application one day a week.

The experience of going from using a mouse to not being able to tell where it’s at on the page can be very jarring. It makes you really understand the importance of keyboard usability!

You can check out No Mouse Days on GitHub if you’re interested in finding out more.

If you don’t want to install a package, you can run a JavaScript snippet in your DevTools Console to add the CSS style of cursor: none; to the body of the page you’re currently on:

document.body.style.cursor = "none"
document.body.style.cursor = "none"

With this method there may still be some elements that will display your cursor but there’s a good chance it will be mostly hidden as you move your mouse around. Reloading or navigating away from the page will put it back to normal.

Regardless of the method you choose, I would suggest making the “no mouse” idea part of your manual testing workflow on a regular basis.

The ARIA Authoring Practices Guide

Whenever you’re building a web application, it’s helpful to follow patterns.

The ARIA Authoring Practices Guide is a wealth of information about the conventions behind the most common controls used in web development. Each of the patterns they outline include a description of expected keyboard interactions.

When you’re tasked with building a custom component, compare it to the list of patterns and see if they can help you build a more intuitive interface.

I do want to note that these patterns aren’t ready to go straight into production. You still need to test them and make sure they work as expected!

Regardless, the ARIA Authoring Practices Guide is definitely worth bookmarking.
